@Times Rita
The referents of the biblical names for flowers are changeable from one translation to the next. In Canticles 2:1, the "rose" of Sharon is 'khavatzelet'. Next door to it the "lily" of the valley is 'shoshanah'. In modern Hebrew, a rose is 'vered', also seen in the diminutive 'vardit'. It was part of the vocabulary established in the 19th C. as part of the revival of Hebrew in the vernacular.
Corrections welcomed from native speakers, as always.

